470–1523","1400–Male":"1400–Overleden","1405–Female":"1405–Overleden","about 1470":"circa 1470","2 February 1523":"2 februari 1523","1451":"1451","1483":"1483","1470":"1470","after 1523":"na 1523","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","1523":"1523","1400":"1400","1510":"1510","1452":"1452","1429":"1429","23 April 1510":"23 april 1510","1405":"1405","East Down, Barnstaple, Devonshire, England":"East Down, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Monk Okehampton, , Devonshire, England":"Monkokehampton, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","East Down, Devon, England":"East Down, Devon, England","Lynton, Devonshire, England":"Lynton, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1429–after 1523":"1429–after 1523","1429–1523":"1429–1523","1424–1483":"1424–1483","1452–1510":"1452–1510","1470–1523":"1470–1523","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","1405–Female":"1405–Deceased","about 1470":"about 1470","2 February 1523":"2 February 1523","1451":"1451","1483":"1483","1470":"1470","after 1523":"after 1523","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","1523":"1523","1400":"1400","1510":"1510","1452":"1452","1429":"1429","23 April 1510":"23 April 1510","1405":"1405","East Down, Barnstaple, Devonshire, England":"East Down, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Monk Okehampton, , Devonshire, England":"Monkokehampton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","East Down, Devon, England":"East Down, Devon, England","Lynton, Devonshire, England":"Lynton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Salle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Pierre.","French: topographic name or a metonymic occupational name for someone who lived or worked at a manor house, from Old French <i>salle</i> ‘large room, hall’. Compare   Desalle   and   Lasalle  .","French (<b>Sallé</b>): from Old French <i>salé</i> ‘salty, salted’, hence a metonymic occupational name for someone who dealt with salt meat or salt fish, or perhaps, in a figurative sense, a nickname for a witty or mordant person. Compare   Sallee   and   Salley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Desalle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Marco, Reno.","Americanized form (also <b>De Salle</b>) of Italian   Di Salle  .","French: shortened form of <b>Delasalle</b>, a variant, with fused preposition <i>de</i> and definite article <i>la</i> ‘from the’, of   Salle   1 ‘large room, hall’."]},{"name":"Sallee","meanings":["French (<b>Sallée</b>): variant of <b>Sallé</b> ‘salted, salty’ (see   Salle  ).","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]},{"name":"Salles","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Luiz, Ricardo, Ana, Armenia, Ernesto, Fabio, Francisco, Gustavo, Jaime, Luzia, Manuel.  French Andre, Emile, Jean-Luc.","French: variant of   Salle   1.","French: habitational name from (Les) Salles, the name of several places in various parts of France."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jane Salle was born in 1429, in Monkokehampton, Devon, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert Salle Esquire, was 29 and her mother, Salle, was 24. She married John Pyne in 1451, in Monkokehampton, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died after 1523."},"et":{"1429–after 1523":"1429–pärast 1523","1429–1523":"1429–1523","1424–1483":"1424–1483","1452–1510":"1452–1510","1470–1523":"1470–1523","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","about 1470":"umbes 1470","2 February 1523":"2. veebruar 1523","1451":"1451","1483":"1483","1470":"1470","after 1523":"pärast 1523","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","1523":"1523","1400":"1400","1510":"1510","1452":"1452","1429":"1429","23 April 1510":"23. aprill 1510","1405":"1405","East Down, Barnstaple, Devonshire, England":"East Down, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Monk Okehampton, , Devonshire, England":"Monkokehampton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","East Down, Devon, England":"East Down, Devon, England","Lynton, Devonshire, England":"Lynton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1429–after 1523":"1429–1523 jälkeen","1429–1523":"1429–1523","1424–1483":"1424–1483","1452–1510":"1452–1510","1470–1523":"1470–1523","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","about 1470":"noin 1470","2 February 1523":"2. helmikuuta 1523","1451":"1451","1483":"1483","1470":"1470","after 1523":"1523 jälkeen","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","1523":"1523","1400":"1400","1510":"1510","1452":"1452","1429":"1429","23 April 1510":"23. huhtikuuta 1510","1405":"1405","East Down, Barnstaple, Devonshire, England":"East Down, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Monk Okehampton, , Devonshire, England":"Monkokehampton, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","East 